    {
      "title": "The Extended Noun (الاسم الممدود)",
      "titleArabic": "الاسم الممدود",
      "content": [
        "The extended noun (الاسم الممدود) ends in hamza preceded by alif (ـَاء). It takes regular case endings.",
        "The hamza can be original, feminine, or substituted - this affects declension."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Ends in ـَاء (alif + hamza)",
        "Takes visible case endings on the hamza",
        "Dual: صَحْرَاءَانِ or صَحْرَاوَانِ",
        "Hamza type determines certain transformations"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "صَحْرَاءُ", "english": "desert" },
        { "arabic": "سَمَاءٌ", "english": "sky" },
        { "arabic": "بِنَاءٌ", "english": "building" },
        { "arabic": "دُعَاءٌ", "english": "supplication" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Types of Hamza in Extended Nouns",
      "titleArabic": "أنواع الهمزة في الاسم الممدود",
      "content": [
        "The hamza in extended nouns can be of three types, each affecting how the word behaves in dual and plural forms.",
        "Understanding the origin of the hamza helps in correct conjugation."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "Original hamza (أصلية): from the root - بِنَاء (ب-ن-ء) - stays as hamza",
        "Feminine hamza (للتأنيث): صَحْرَاء - becomes وَاو in dual: صَحْرَاوَانِ",
        "Substituted hamza (منقلبة): سَمَاء (from سَمَو) - can be وَاو or hamza",
        "Pattern affects nisbah: صَحْرَاوِيّ، سَمَائِيّ"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "صَحْرَاوَانِ", "english": "two deserts" },
        { "arabic": "سَمَاوَاتٌ", "english": "heavens / skies" },
        { "arabic": "أَبْنَاءٌ", "english": "sons (pl. of اِبْن)" },
        { "arabic": "أَصْدِقَاءُ", "english": "friends" }
      ]
    }
